time required: 35 minutes
---

Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1%unit}(peeled and diced). Thinly slice half the @jalapeño{1%unit} into rounds; mince remaining half. 

> TIP: Remove ribs and seeds for less heat.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add onion and minced jalapeño; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add @ground beef{10%ounce}, @Mexican spice blend{1%tablespoon}, @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon}, salt, and pepper to same #pot{}. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir @tomato paste{1.5%ounce} into pot. Cook, stirring, until dark red and combined, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add @diced tomatoes{14%ounce}, @black beans{13.4%ounce} and their liquid, @beef stock concentrate{1%unit}, @water{¼%cup}, salt, and pepper; stir to combine. Bring to a simmer and cook, uncovered, until thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}. Turn off heat. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{2%tablespoon} and @hot sauce{1%teaspoon} to taste; season with salt and pepper. Stir in water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Divide chili between #bowls{}. Top with @Monterey Jack cheese{¼%cup}, crema, and as much sliced jalapeño as you like.

> A good chili has well-seasoned beef, creamy beans, and tender vegetables. A great chili, however, has all that and comes together in one pot in under an hour. This chili is one of the greats. And once you take a bite, we can guarantee you'll agree. Not to mention, these beefy bowls are adorned with some delicious fixings: tangy hot sauce crema and melty Monterey Jack. If you've got some on hand, why not crumble up some tortilla chips and sprinkle them on top for a crunch?